[[Image:Chiprovski-monastery-church-graveyard-and-ossuary.jpg|right|thumb|300px|View of the church, the graveyard and the tower]] '''Chiprovtsi Monastery''' ({{lang-bg|Чипровски манастир}}, ''Chiprovski manastir'') is a [[Bulgarian Orthodox]] monastery 5 kilometres northeast of the town of [[Chiprovtsi]] in [[Montana Province]] in northwestern [[Bulgaria]]. It belongs to the diocese of [[Vidin]] and lies in the valley of the [[Ogosta]] river.
According to Petar Bogdan, the monastery was built in the 10th century and remained a religious and cultural centre despite [[Tatars|Tatar]] and [[Magyars|Magyar]] raids in the 13th century, the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] invasion in the 14th century and [[Michael the Brave]]'s raids in the 16th century. The monastery has been razed six times, in 1412, 1688, 1806, 1828, 1837 and 1876, with the one of 1688 after the [[Chiprovtsi Uprising]] being particularly devastating. The current monastery church was built in 1829.
The Chiprovtsi Monastery consists of a church dedicated to Saint [[John of Rila]], residential buildings, a small graveyard and a three-storey tower featuring an ossuary, a chapel and a belfry.
